  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Posthumous Title Certificate for Queen Songpyeong
  author: Anonymous
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When merit is exalted, honors are deepened. When virtue abounds, the posthumous name grows sacred. Thus do we consult the ancient records and present these great tributes.

    We humbly reflect that the late Queen possessed the finest qualities of the royal clan, being the daughter of a princess. The Sage Emperor, perceiving her noble character, raised her within the palace. The Former Emperor chose her as consort, entrusting her with the inner chambers. She bore a jewel of the realm and became the partner of this throne. Yet like a dream she departed in an instant—though our grief may span a thousand autumns, her many descendants shall carry forward her legacy through ten thousand ages.

    All the virtues of this consort flowed from her mother's teachings. Why then did she not fulfill her years? Why did her final hour arrive so suddenly? The spirits dwell in darkness beyond our understanding; heaven's ways remain inscrutable.

    We can only surmise that through her trials and arduous trials of long ago, the burdens of care accumulated until they turned to illness. We shed tears without cease and belatedly offer these words of lasting honor.

    We reverently dispatch our officials to present this sacred edict, bestowing upon her the posthumous title of Queen Songpyeong. May her spirit in heaven accept this noble designation with grace.
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal edict bestowing a posthumous name (시호) upon a royal consort, following the classical Chinese court tradition. The document serves both as eulogy and official proclamation.
    - The 'dream' (꿈결같이) references the Buddhist concept of the illusory nature of life and the sudden impermanence of worldly existence.
    - References to the 'Sage Emperor' and 'Former Emperor' indicate the hierarchical succession and the consort's place across multiple reigns.
